{"term": "2010", "caseName": "Staub v. Proctor Hospital", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010/09-400", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - November 02, 2010", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/21423", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We will hear argument this afternoon in Case 09-400, Staub v. Proctor Hospital.", "start": 0, "stop": 8.903, "duration": 8.9}, {"text": "Mr. Schnapper.", "start": 8.903, "stop": 9.605, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 9.605, "stop": 10.198, "duration": 0.59}, {"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 10.198, "stop": 12.666, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "The dismissal of an employee is often the result of the interrelated actions and decisions of several officials.", "start": 12.666, "stop": 19.787, "duration": 7.12}, {"text": "Whether an employer is legally responsible for any particular official and his or her actions and decisions turns on agency law.", "start": 19.787, "stop": 29.94, "duration": 10.15}, {"text": "Congress legislates against a background of agency law and is presumed to have intended agency principles to govern that kind of question.", "start": 29.94, "stop": 37.623, "duration": 7.68}, {"text": "Agency law, not the Eleventh Circuit's \"cat's paw\" doctrine, is the controlling standard here.", "start": 37.623, "stop": 43.682, "duration": 6.06}, {"text": "There are two principal agency doctrines on which liability can be based.", "start": 43.682, "stop": 50.261, "duration": 6.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, before we jump to agency law, shouldn't we take a look at the language of the statute?", "start": 50.261, "stop": 55.288, "duration": 5.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 55.288, "stop": 58.115, "duration": 2.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the statute says that a prima facie case is made out if it is shown that military service, anti-military animus, was a motivating factor in the employer's action.", "start": 58.115, "stop": 71.268, "duration": 13.15}, {"text": "The employer's action here was discharge, right?", "start": 71.268, "stop": 76.435, "duration": 5.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct.", "start": 76.435, "stop": 76.812, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the word \"motivate\" means to provide someone with a motive to do something, right?", "start": 76.812, "stop": 83.122, "duration": 6.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 83.122, "stop": 84.417, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the person who did something here was the person who discharged, discharged Mr. Staub, right?", "start": 84.417, "stop": 92.805, "duration": 8.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's not the--", "start": 92.805, "stop": 94.462, "duration": 1.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So why doesn't it follow that the motivation that is relevant under the statute is the motivation of the person who -- who performs the action that is challenged?", "start": 94.462, "stop": 104.549, "duration": 10.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, there is a -- there are a series of actions and decisions that yield this result.", "start": 104.549, "stop": 110.328, "duration": 5.78}, {"text": "And the reference in the statute is to the actions of the employer, not to any particular official.", "start": 110.328, "stop": 115.889, "duration": 5.56}, {"text": "And so--", "start": 115.889, "stop": 116.467, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, but the -- what is -- what is made illegal are certain employer actions, right?", "start": 116.467, "stop": 122.667, "duration": 6.2}, {"text": "Not everything that's done, not -- just writing up a bad report for a biased reason is not actionable under this statute; isn't that correct?", "start": 122.667, "stop": 131.632, "duration": 8.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's correct.", "start": 131.632, "stop": 133.024, "duration": 1.39}, {"text": "But a decision to -- the decision to dismiss an official is -- can be, and is here, the result, cumulative result, of a series of decisions.", "start": 133.024, "stop": 144.141, "duration": 11.12}, {"text": "It's not unlike what occurs in the criminal justice system.", "start": 144.141, "stop": 149.511, "duration": 5.37}, {"text": "Only a sentencing judge can send a defendant to prison, but that decision actually is a result of a series of other decisions, all of which are government action.", "start": 149.511, "stop": 159.775, "duration": 10.26}, {"text": "We think--", "start": 159.775, "stop": 160.352, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "But you say that those decisions that contribute have to be decisions by supervisory personnel.", "start": 160.352, "stop": 168.381, "duration": 8.03}, {"text": "If your theory is correct, I don't know why that is so.", "start": 168.381, "stop": 172.051, "duration": 3.67}, {"text": "I don't know why a co-employee who has a hostile motivation and makes a report to the supervisor who ultimately dismisses the individual, why that -- that wouldn't qualify as well.", "start": 172.051, "stop": 188.276, "duration": 16.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, our standard is not whether it's a supervisor, but whether it's an official for whom the employer is liable under agency law.", "start": 188.276, "stop": 196.005, "duration": 7.73}, {"text": "That would not be every supervisor.", "start": 196.005, "stop": 197.802, "duration": 1.8}, {"text": "If a supervisor unrelated to this particular department put a false charge in a suggestion box, that wouldn't be any different.", "start": 197.802, "stop": 209.673, "duration": 11.87}, {"text": "Ordinarily, a coworker wouldn't qualify under agency principles as an agent of the employer when engaging in that conduct.", "start": 209.673, "stop": 218.576, "duration": 8.9}, {"text": "You have to look at the specific conduct and apply the traditional agency standards.", "start": 218.576, "stop": 223.228, "duration": 4.65}, {"text": "They are laid out, for example, in the Court's decision in Ellerth, which refers to the two branches of agency law: Scope of employment, and action which is aided in, where the actor was aided in the conduct by his or her official position.", "start": 223.228, "stop": 239.005, "duration": 15.78}, {"text": "And I think those principles would not ordinarily apply to a coworker, but they would also not apply invariably to a supervisor.", "start": 239.005, "stop": 248.204, "duration": 9.2}, {"text": "This is not -- we are not advocating the supervisor versus non-supervisor distinction in Ellerth, but a return to just the traditional agency doctrines.", "start": 248.204, "stop": 258.823, "duration": 10.62}, {"text": "And we think those doctrines delineate who is the employer for the purposes of the statute, which bans action by the employer.", "start": 258.823, "stop": 267.133, "duration": 8.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "The employer would be liable for these lower supervisory employees here why?", "start": 267.133, "stop": 273.254, "duration": 6.12}, {"text": "Did they have authority to discharge?", "start": 273.254, "stop": 275.957, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, they had other authorities.", "start": 275.957, "stop": 278.659, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "They had -- well, there are two doctrines.", "start": 278.659, "stop": 280.737, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why do they stand in different shoes from a co-employee who also contributes to the ultimate decision to fire?", "start": 280.737, "stop": 288.856, "duration": 8.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it's -- it's the core responsibility of -- in terms of scope of employment.", "start": 288.856, "stop": 294.448, "duration": 5.59}, {"text": "It's the core responsibility of a supervisor of a particular individual to be monitoring his or her behavior, reporting on it, perhaps initiating disciplinary matters -- measures.", "start": 294.448, "stop": 305.163, "duration": 10.72}, {"text": "That wouldn't be true of all supervisors.", "start": 305.163, "stop": 307.445, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "It's only true of Mr. Staub's supervisors.", "start": 307.445, "stop": 309.504, "duration": 2.06}, {"text": "So -- what -- the kind of thing they did was the kind of work that they were employed to engage in, and that distinguishes them from, say, another supervisor who might slip a note into a suggestion box.", "start": 309.504, "stop": 322.454, "duration": 12.95}, {"text": "Second, the other branch, major branch, of agency law is that an employer is liable for actions of individuals when their conduct -- when they are aided in their conduct by their official position, which would not typically be true of a fellow worker.", "start": 322.454, "stop": 340.041, "duration": 17.59}, {"text": "But that could be true here.", "start": 340.041, "stop": 341.632, "duration": 1.59}, {"text": "For example, Mulally set much of this in motion when, on the plaintiff's version of the facts, she issued the January 27th corrective order.", "start": 341.632, "stop": 351.564, "duration": 9.93}, {"text": "Everyone agrees she wrote it.", "start": 351.564, "stop": 353.421, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "She signed it.", "start": 353.421, "stop": 353.951, "duration": 0.53}, {"text": "She was aided in doing that by her position as a supervisor.", "start": 353.951, "stop": 358.232, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "A coworker couldn't do that.", "start": 358.232, "stop": 359.356, "duration": 1.12}, {"text": "And indeed, somebody else's supervisor couldn't have done that.", "start": 359.356, "stop": 362.089, "duration": 2.73}, {"text": "So--", "start": 362.089, "stop": 362.682, "duration": 0.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could I just ask where -- could I ask where your argument leads?", "start": 362.682, "stop": 367.759, "duration": 5.08}, {"text": "Let's say that an employer calls in an employee and says: Now, we have to decide who to lay off, and we have looked at your record over the last 10 years, and here it is, all the evaluations you've gotten over the past 10 years, and based on all of that, we -- we've decide that you are going to be the person to be laid off.", "start": 367.759, "stop": 390.076, "duration": 22.32}, {"text": "Now if it turns out that one of those evaluations was rendered by someone who had an anti-military bias, would that make the employee -- would that be a prima facie case against the employer?", "start": 390.076, "stop": 403.884, "duration": 13.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It would.", "start": 403.884, "stop": 405.76, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "But the affirmative--", "start": 405.76, "stop": 407.522, "duration": 1.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Even -- even if the employer at that time did every -- made every reasonable effort to investigate the validity of all the prior evaluations, still the employer would be on the hook?", "start": 407.522, "stop": 416.174, "duration": 8.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 416.174, "stop": 417.176, "duration": 1}, {"text": "There is nothing in the statute or in the common law that creates a special rule for thorough investigation.", "start": 417.176, "stop": 423.097, "duration": 5.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's a sweeping rule.", "start": 423.097, "stop": 424.204, "duration": 1.11}, {"text": "I was going to ask a related hypothetical.", "start": 424.204, "stop": 426.688, "duration": 2.48}, {"text": "Suppose the -- the officer who is in charge, charged with the decision to terminate or not to terminate says: I'm going to have a hearing.", "start": 426.688, "stop": 434.011, "duration": 7.32}, {"text": "You can both have counsel.", "start": 434.011, "stop": 435.498, "duration": 1.49}, {"text": "And you have who, is it -- suppose Buck -- suppose the two employees that were allegedly anti-military here testified and they said there was no anti-military bias, and the person is then terminated.", "start": 435.498, "stop": 457.174, "duration": 21.68}, {"text": "Later the employee has evidence that those two were lying.", "start": 457.174, "stop": 463.296, "duration": 6.12}, {"text": "Could he bring an action then?", "start": 463.296, "stop": 467.235, "duration": 3.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 467.235, "stop": 468.187, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's sweeping.", "start": 468.187, "stop": 469.591, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "That's almost an insurer's liability insofar as the director of employment is concerned.", "start": 469.591, "stop": 475.261, "duration": 5.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's--", "start": 475.261, "stop": 475.791, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "He has to insure.", "start": 475.791, "stop": 477.059, "duration": 1.27}, {"text": "He has -- he has done everything he can, he has an hearing, and he has almost absolute liability.", "start": 477.059, "stop": 482.241, "duration": 5.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Respondeat -- respondeat superior is absolute liability.", "start": 482.241, "stop": 485.553, "duration": 3.31}, {"text": "There is no due diligence exception.", "start": 485.553, "stop": 488.177, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "If you look to section 219 of the Restatement of Agency, 219 part 2(b) provides for liability based on negligence, but part 2(d), regardless of whether there is negligence, provides liability if you're added in your -- aided in your conduct by the -- by your position.", "start": 488.177, "stop": 512.509, "duration": 24.33}, {"text": "Now, it's possible, depending on the exact facts, that the situation you described wouldn't fit into scope of employment or aided in.", "start": 512.509, "stop": 522.134, "duration": 9.63}, {"text": "If you just had two people whose only role was just as witnesses, then they're not acting as agents, they are just witnesses, perhaps.", "start": 522.134, "stop": 527.803, "duration": 5.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there is--", "start": 527.803, "stop": 528.598, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there is no--", "start": 528.598, "stop": 529.628, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--There is this defense for the employer that, no matter that there was this ill will, there was enough else to warrant termination of this employee.", "start": 529.628, "stop": 545.451, "duration": 15.82}, {"text": "And so the--", "start": 545.451, "stop": 547.479, "duration": 2.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's correct, Your Honor.", "start": 547.479, "stop": 550.385, "duration": 2.91}, {"text": "And it's the language of section 4311(c)(1) that is critical here.", "start": 550.385, "stop": 556.118, "duration": 5.73}, {"text": "The statute provides that if an improper motive was a motivating factor there is a defense.", "start": 556.118, "stop": 564.817, "duration": 8.7}, {"text": "But there is only one defense, and the defense is a showing the employer would have fired the plaintiff anyway.", "start": 564.817, "stop": 569.376, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "The language is mandatory.", "start": 569.376, "stop": 571.86, "duration": 2.48}, {"text": "It says if the defense is not made out, the employer shall be considered to have violated the statute.", "start": 571.86, "stop": 578.31, "duration": 6.45}, {"text": "But the clearest enunciation of the error in the Seventh Circuit is the language at page 47 of the Joint Appendix where the court says: Without regard to the jury verdict here, the employer is off the hook if the decisionmaker did her own investigation.", "start": 578.31, "stop": 595.865, "duration": 17.56}, {"text": "That's an additional defense.", "start": 595.865, "stop": 597.49, "duration": 1.63}, {"text": "And it's simply inconsistent with the language of the statute.", "start": 597.49, "stop": 600.095, "duration": 2.61}, {"text": "Now, that may not have been -- that may have been harsh, but it's what the statute says.", "start": 600.095, "stop": 604.56, "duration": 4.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That isn't what the statute says.", "start": 604.56, "stop": 606.717, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "You jump over the language of the statute.", "start": 606.717, "stop": 609.17, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "It has to be a motivating factor in the decision to discharge.", "start": 609.17, "stop": 614.102, "duration": 4.93}, {"text": "And that speaks -- that looks natural -- the natural reading of that is that it looks at the motivation of the person who actually makes the decision to discharge.", "start": 614.102, "stop": 624.817, "duration": 10.72}, {"text": "Now, I'm not suggesting that's the right rule.", "start": 624.817, "stop": 627.145, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "That's a very unattractive rule.", "start": 627.145, "stop": 629.345, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "But the rule that you have suggested is also a very unattractive rule, one that I doubt the Congress intended to adopt.", "start": 629.345, "stop": 638.782, "duration": 9.44}, {"text": "Is there no reasonable middle position here?", "start": 638.782, "stop": 641.465, "duration": 2.68}, {"text": "It's all or nothing?", "start": 641.465, "stop": 642.53, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that the kind of circumstances that the Court has pointed to would be at the remedy stage.", "start": 642.53, "stop": 649.291, "duration": 6.76}, {"text": "The remedies are discretionary and, whereas 4311(c)(1) says 4323 in describing all the remedies says \"may\".", "start": 649.291, "stop": 662.098, "duration": 12.81}, {"text": "And so a court could take those things into account in framing a remedy.", "start": 662.098, "stop": 667.549, "duration": 5.45}, {"text": "And certainly the good faith efforts of someone in Buck's position, for example, would be relevant to a determination of whether a violation was willful.", "start": 667.549, "stop": 677.266, "duration": 9.72}, {"text": "And that in fact reflects what happened in this case, which is that the jury found that there was a violation -- found that the -- the motivations involved here included an improper motivation, rejected the 4311(c)(1) defense, but then found the violation wasn't willful.", "start": 677.266, "stop": 698.273, "duration": 21.01}, {"text": "So I think, given the structure of the statute, the play here, the ability to adjust to those circumstances, is in the remedy provision, not in the mandatory language of the 4311(c)(1).", "start": 698.273, "stop": 709.344, "duration": 11.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't that -- the government's formulation that the discrimination has to play a substantial role in the termination a limiting principle?", "start": 709.344, "stop": 723.308, "duration": 13.96}, {"text": "I mean, you answered or appeared to be answering Justice Alito that in a 10-year history if one report of discrimination existed that that would shift the burden to the employer.", "start": 723.308, "stop": 738.068, "duration": 14.76}, {"text": "Is that an accurate statement of law?", "start": 738.068, "stop": 741.488, "duration": 3.42}, {"text": "That one report has to play a role that is more than a mere existence, doesn't it?", "start": 741.488, "stop": 748.299, "duration": 6.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in that regard I think we would articulate the standard differently.", "start": 748.299, "stop": 752.234, "duration": 3.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Than the SG?", "start": 752.234, "stop": 753.31, "duration": 1.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 753.31, "stop": 754.016, "duration": 0.71}, {"text": "The language in the statute is not a substantial motivating factor.", "start": 754.016, "stop": 757.498, "duration": 3.48}, {"text": "It's a motivating factor.", "start": 757.498, "stop": 759.058, "duration": 1.56}, {"text": "And that choice of language is clearly deliberate.", "start": 759.058, "stop": 762.042, "duration": 2.98}, {"text": "This whole -- this language in this provision derives from this Court's decision in Price Waterhouse--", "start": 762.042, "stop": 768.227, "duration": 6.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it has to have some materiality to the decision.", "start": 768.227, "stop": 772.898, "duration": 4.67}, {"text": "I mean, it has to have -- it has to play not just any role.", "start": 772.898, "stop": 778.553, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "It has to play a material role in the decision, no?", "start": 778.553, "stop": 782.191, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "Or -- they use \"substantial\".", "start": 782.191, "stop": 784.424, "duration": 2.23}, {"text": "It could be \"material\".", "start": 784.424, "stop": 785.439, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--If I could go back to Price Waterhouse and explain how we got to this language.", "start": 785.439, "stop": 789.061, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "It was a sharply divide opinion.", "start": 789.061, "stop": 791.56, "duration": 2.5}, {"text": "The plurality standard of Justice Brennan said \"a motivating factor\".", "start": 791.56, "stop": 794.934, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "Justice White's standard was \"a substantial motivating factor\".", "start": 794.934, "stop": 798.681, "duration": 3.75}, {"text": "Justice O'Connor's standard was \"substantial\".", "start": 798.681, "stop": 801.415, "duration": 2.73}, {"text": "Justice Kennedy pointed out in his dissenting opinion that was going to lead to fights about how much was enough to be substantial.", "start": 801.415, "stop": 807.335, "duration": 5.92}, {"text": "When Congress then wrote the 1991 Civil Rights Act, from which this language derives, amending Title VII they used the Brennan language, \"a motivating factor\".", "start": 807.335, "stop": 818.191, "duration": 10.86}, {"text": "They didn't use \"substantial\" and I think that was clearly deliberate.", "start": 818.191, "stop": 820.862, "duration": 2.67}, {"text": "Anyone who read Price Waterhouse -- and that provision was written about Price Waterhouse -- would have understood that that was a difference within the Court and they made that choice.", "start": 820.862, "stop": 830.076, "duration": 9.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Schnapper, I guess this goes back to Justice Alito's question.", "start": 830.076, "stop": 833.746, "duration": 3.67}, {"text": "I find it difficult to grasp the distinction that you draw or what is seems could possibly exist between a willful motivating factor and a non-willful motivating factor.", "start": 833.746, "stop": 848.677, "duration": 14.93}, {"text": "I mean, to say that it's motivating is -- is to say that it's willful, it seems to me.", "start": 848.677, "stop": 855.44, "duration": 6.76}, {"text": "But you want us to draw a distinction between a willful motivating factor and a non-willful motivating factor?", "start": 855.44, "stop": 861.499, "duration": 6.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's not our position, Justice Scalia.", "start": 861.499, "stop": 864.264, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "Our position is that, with regard to the liability determination in 4311, that any motivating factor is what is required.", "start": 864.264, "stop": 872.897, "duration": 8.63}, {"text": "If you have a number of different officials involved, Buck and Mulally and Korenchuk, if anyone who played a role in this had an unlawful motive that satisfies 4311(c)(1) and the burden shifts to the employer to show it would have done the same thing anyway.", "start": 872.897, "stop": 888.846, "duration": 15.95}, {"text": "Willfulness doesn't have that same language about a motivating factor.", "start": 888.846, "stop": 894.158, "duration": 5.31}, {"text": "It just asks whether the employer's violation was willful.", "start": 894.158, "stop": 897.047, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "This Court's decision about willfulness in Thurston and Hazen Paper I think are broad enough to encompass a situation where you had several different officials.", "start": 897.047, "stop": 906.371, "duration": 9.32}, {"text": "And if I might--", "start": 906.371, "stop": 907.729, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You want to hold the employer liable for the actions of these other officials, other than the one who did the firing.", "start": 907.729, "stop": 919.551, "duration": 11.82}, {"text": "And if they are liable for -- if you hold them the employer liable for their contribution to the firing, it seems to me you have to hold him liable for their willfulness as well.", "start": 919.551, "stop": 930.236, "duration": 10.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It's our view that the language of the statute permits that distinction because of the discretionary nature of the remedy provision as opposed to the mandatory nature of 4311(c)(1).", "start": 930.236, "stop": 940.652, "duration": 10.42}, {"text": "I would like to reserve the balance of my time.", "start": 940.652, "stop": 942.667, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Schnapper.", "start": 942.667, "stop": 943.572, "duration": 0.9}, {"text": "Mr. Miller.", "start": 943.572, "stop": 956.101, "duration": 12.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 956.101, "stop": 958.818, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "An employer is liable under USERRA when a supervisor acting with a discriminatory motive uses a delegated authority to cause an adverse employment action.", "start": 958.818, "stop": 967.422, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "The court of appeals held that liability does not attach unless that supervisor exerts singular influence over the decisionmaker.", "start": 967.422, "stop": 975.482, "duration": 8.06}, {"text": "But that standard is inconsistent with the statute for two reasons.", "start": 975.482, "stop": 979.23, "duration": 3.75}, {"text": "First, it's incompatible with the statutory definition of \"employer\", which includes not just the ultimate decisionmaker, but any person to whom the employer has delegated the performance of significant employment responsibilities.", "start": 979.23, "stop": 991.49, "duration": 12.26}, {"text": "Second, it's contrary to the statute's causation standard, which requires only that military status be a motivating factor, not necessarily a singularly important factor or the determinative factor in the adverse employment action.", "start": 991.49, "stop": 1006.592, "duration": 15.1}, {"text": "Now--", "start": 1006.592, "stop": 1007.747, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you regard -- is that the same as a but-for cause, motivating factor?", "start": 1007.747, "stop": 1012.649, "duration": 4.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No.", "start": 1012.649, "stop": 1014.057, "duration": 1.41}, {"text": "There is two separate components to the inquiry.", "start": 1014.057, "stop": 1016.038, "duration": 1.98}, {"text": "First -- the first is that it has to be a motivating factor, and that is the plaintiff's burden to establish in order to make a prima facie case under section 4311(c).", "start": 1016.038, "stop": 1024.177, "duration": 8.14}, {"text": "And then there is an affirmative defense if the employer can show that it was not a but-for factor in the sense that, you know, even had the person not been in the military the same action would have been taken.", "start": 1024.177, "stop": 1036.592, "duration": 12.42}, {"text": "That's the -- if the employer can show that, then it's absolved of liability.", "start": 1036.592, "stop": 1041.731, "duration": 5.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you using proximate cause in but-for, or are you suggesting a different formulation of causation?", "start": 1041.731, "stop": 1049.838, "duration": 8.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "In our view the \"motivating factor\" language captures the idea of proximate cause.", "start": 1049.838, "stop": 1055.586, "duration": 5.75}, {"text": "Something can be a motivating factor if it is one of many factors, but in our view it does need to be more than a trivial or de minimus factor and if you have a situation where the bias -- the action of the biased supervisor leads through a long and improbable and unforeseeable chain of causation to the adverse employment action, you might have a but-for cause but you wouldn't have proximate cause and it wouldn't be a motivating factor.", "start": 1055.586, "stop": 1084.587, "duration": 29}, {"text": "Now, this case, and I think most real world cases, are quite different from that.", "start": 1084.587, "stop": 1088.837, "duration": 4.25}, {"text": "Here we have a termination decision and that was made by Buck on the basis of the January 27th warning that was given to Petitioner and the report that Petitioner had not complied with that warning.", "start": 1088.837, "stop": 1101.394, "duration": 12.56}, {"text": "And both parts of that, the warning issued by Mulally and the report of noncompliance that came from Korenchuk, both parts of that the jury could have concluded were--", "start": 1101.394, "stop": 1111.111, "duration": 9.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "In that formulation as you've just articulated, where do you place your test of a subordinate setting in motion and playing a substantial role?", "start": 1111.111, "stop": 1122.306, "duration": 11.19}, {"text": "What does that test that you proposed in your brief -- how does it fit into this?", "start": 1122.306, "stop": 1128.008, "duration": 5.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The -- the discriminatorily motivated actions in this case, the evidence interpreted in the light most favorable to Petitioner, were the decision of Mulally to write up Petitioner for this January 27th incident, and that was motivated by her hostility to him because of his status in the Army Reserves; and then the decision of Korenchuk to report that he had violated the terms of that January 27th warning, and that was also motivated by his hostility to Petitioner's membership in the -- in the Army Reserves.", "start": 1128.008, "stop": 1166.18, "duration": 38.17}, {"text": "And both of those decisions had a substantial causal role in the -- in the ultimate decision made by the employer to terminate.", "start": 1166.18, "stop": 1173.398, "duration": 7.22}, {"text": "And because both of those people, Mulally and Korenchuk--", "start": 1173.398, "stop": 1176.569, "duration": 3.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your -- Petitioner's counsel argues that there is no issue of -- in the motivating factor test, it doesn't have to be a substantial role; it just has to be a motivating factor, so that the subordinates--", "start": 1176.569, "stop": 1192.357, "duration": 15.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, this may just be a semantic disagreement.", "start": 1192.357, "stop": 1197.2, "duration": 4.84}, {"text": "We don't think it has to be substantial in the sense of predominant.", "start": 1197.2, "stop": 1200.433, "duration": 3.23}, {"text": "It can be one of -- there can be many factors and as long as it's one of them that's a motivating factor.", "start": 1200.433, "stop": 1206.353, "duration": 5.92}, {"text": "But it needs to be substantial in the sense of more than de minimus or more than trivial, something that the employer actually took into account as one of the reasons--", "start": 1206.353, "stop": 1214.648, "duration": 8.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What happens in the situation where a prior evaluation or some disciplinary action does have a substantial effect on the decision that's -- the employment decision that's made, but the employer has no notice that the prior evaluation or disciplinary action was based on a biased ground, or any reasonable way of finding out that it was based on a biased ground?", "start": 1214.648, "stop": 1240.981, "duration": 26.33}, {"text": "What happens in that situation?", "start": 1240.981, "stop": 1242.588, "duration": 1.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--There would still be liability just as there is liability in the situation, which is quite common, where an employer gives a single official the authority to both observe an employee's behavior and make a decision to terminate.", "start": 1242.588, "stop": 1255.425, "duration": 12.84}, {"text": "If that single official is biased, and makes a decision on the basis of that bias, then the employer is going to be liable even if the people who hired that official tried very hard to make sure that he wasn't biased.", "start": 1255.425, "stop": 1269.701, "duration": 14.28}, {"text": "And that's consistent with--", "start": 1269.701, "stop": 1271.654, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you get around the statutory language that says that the motivating, it has to be a motivating factor in the -- in the action that is challenged?", "start": 1271.654, "stop": 1280.557, "duration": 8.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It -- it has to be a motivating -- the statute says a motivating factor in the employer's action.", "start": 1280.557, "stop": 1286.554, "duration": 6}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the employer's action here is -- is discharge.", "start": 1286.554, "stop": 1289.226, "duration": 2.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, and the employer -- the employer is a corporation, and it's -- so you have to look at which individuals do you look at in figuring out whether it was a motivating factor or not, and the statute tells us that.", "start": 1289.226, "stop": 1301.065, "duration": 11.84}, {"text": "In the definition of 4303 it says that the employer includes everyone who has been delegated the performance of employment-related responsibilities.", "start": 1301.065, "stop": 1310.591, "duration": 9.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but those other people -- everybody who has been delegated authority under the -- by the employer are not -- is not involved in the action that's challenged--", "start": 1310.591, "stop": 1320.713, "duration": 10.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "They--", "start": 1320.713, "stop": 1321.555, "duration": 0.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--does not take the action of this challenge.", "start": 1321.555, "stop": 1324.025, "duration": 2.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--They are not the last person who signs the piece of paper, but they certainly are part of the employer's--", "start": 1324.025, "stop": 1330.443, "duration": 6.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So maybe then the test is whether they were delegated some of the responsibility for the challenged action, were they delegated responsibility for making the discharge decision.", "start": 1330.443, "stop": 1340.5, "duration": 10.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--They -- they were delegated supervisory responsibility by the -- by the employer, the authority to observe the people under their supervision, to evaluate and report on their performance, the authority to initiate disciplinary proceedings.", "start": 1340.5, "stop": 1355.009, "duration": 14.51}, {"text": "And they used that authority in a discriminatory manner and that, that conduct by them, was a substantial causal factor in the -- in the ultimate action of discharge.", "start": 1355.009, "stop": 1366.069, "duration": 11.06}, {"text": "And given the -- the statutory definition of employer and the motivating factor causation standard, that's enough under the statute for -- for liability.", "start": 1366.069, "stop": 1376.863, "duration": 10.79}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about a situation where a particular procedure such as the one here is set up for a discriminatory reason, and the employee is really upset with that, and so he, you know, starts a fire in the plant?", "start": 1376.863, "stop": 1392.497, "duration": 15.63}, {"text": "Wouldn't have had -- wouldn't have set the fire if not for the discriminatory purpose.", "start": 1392.497, "stop": 1397.698, "duration": 5.2}, {"text": "Now does he have a cause of action in that case when he is fired for setting -- setting the office on fire?", "start": 1397.698, "stop": 1403.851, "duration": 6.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, even though, as you say, in a sense there would be but-for causation.", "start": 1403.851, "stop": 1408.721, "duration": 4.87}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1408.721, "stop": 1409.381, "duration": 0.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it is not -- it is not under any standard of proximate causation, and not -- the initial discriminatory discipline or warning would not be a motivating or substantial factor in the ultimate decision to fire him.", "start": 1409.381, "stop": 1425.966, "duration": 16.58}, {"text": "He is being fired because of the intervening cause, but--", "start": 1425.966, "stop": 1427.935, "duration": 1.97}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So you do accept that the traditional doctrine of an intervening cause is applicable in this?", "start": 1427.935, "stop": 1434.478, "duration": 6.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Some independent intervening cause.", "start": 1434.478, "stop": 1437.102, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "Now, in this case we don't have anything like that.", "start": 1437.102, "stop": 1438.9, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but what -- what independent intervening cause--", "start": 1438.9, "stop": 1441.24, "duration": 2.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Independent of the employer.", "start": 1441.24, "stop": 1442.881, "duration": 1.64}, {"text": "In this case, we have a number of people, all of whom are agents of the same employer.", "start": 1442.881, "stop": 1447.631, "duration": 4.75}, {"text": "So under traditional principles of -- of an intervening cause, one can't say that any one of those agents of the employer was an intervening cause that broke the chain of causation from misconduct of the other agent of the employer.", "start": 1447.631, "stop": 1462.391, "duration": 14.76}, {"text": "You have a series of agents of the same employer engaging in a course of conduct that at the beginning of which is an unlawfully -- unlawful discriminatory motive that leads to the termination.", "start": 1462.391, "stop": 1475.899, "duration": 13.51}, {"text": "That's quite different from the employee deciding to start a fire or engage in some sort of misconduct that has nothing to do with his military status.", "start": 1475.899, "stop": 1485.908, "duration": 10.01}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I'm sorry -- but I think the end there just kind of glided over the whole issue.", "start": 1485.908, "stop": 1490.845, "duration": 4.94}, {"text": "You say it had nothing to do with his military status.", "start": 1490.845, "stop": 1493.126, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "It has to do with a procedure that was set up because the employer was discriminating against him because of his military status.", "start": 1493.126, "stop": 1501.203, "duration": 8.08}, {"text": "So it certainly had something to do with his military status.", "start": 1501.203, "stop": 1504.436, "duration": 3.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is not, I think it -- one would hope it is not a foreseeable result of discipline given to an employee that he would then start a fire.", "start": 1504.436, "stop": 1512.243, "duration": 7.81}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I know, but the hypothetical is extreme to try to flesh out your position.", "start": 1512.243, "stop": 1517.257, "duration": 5.01}, {"text": "You can certainly imagine an employee reacting in a particular way by being put through procedures that were set up in a discriminatory manner, that would seem to anybody to be a basis for termination, even though the groundwork was laid by the discriminatory procedure.", "start": 1517.257, "stop": 1533.406, "duration": 16.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "One would not normally think that, even if it's less extreme than starting a fire, that a course of misconduct by the employee is a foreseeable result of a discriminatory--", "start": 1533.406, "stop": 1545.728, "duration": 12.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Wouldn't it -- wouldn't the employer's defense simply be: Anyone who starts a fire goes?", "start": 1545.728, "stop": 1558.818, "duration": 13.09}, {"text": "That's -- that's a -- it would have happened no matter what the reason was.", "start": 1558.818, "stop": 1567.97, "duration": 9.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 1567.97, "stop": 1569.452, "duration": 1.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "That just comes under the employer's defense as showing that the same action would have been taken.", "start": 1569.452, "stop": 1577.216, "duration": 7.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric D. Miller", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1577.216, "stop": 1577.981, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 1577.981, "stop": 1579.135, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "Mr. Davis.", "start": 1579.135, "stop": 1585.663, "duration": 6.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 1585.663, "stop": 1588.789, "duration": 3.13}, {"text": "The parties to this case are in total agreement with respect to two points.", "start": 1588.789, "stop": 1593.8, "duration": 5.01}, {"text": "The first point is that Linda Buck made the decision to fire Vincent Staub.", "start": 1593.8, "stop": 1599.44, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "And the second point is, there is no evidence whatsoever that Linda Buck possessed animus towards Mr. Staub on account of his service in the Reserve.", "start": 1599.44, "stop": 1608.046, "duration": 8.61}, {"text": "Applying ordinary tort-related vicarious liability rules, Staub's case against Proctor Hospital would end right here.", "start": 1608.046, "stop": 1616.62, "duration": 8.57}, {"text": "But the Seventh Circuit, applying what it calls the \"cat's paw\" doctrine, gives Staub and all other plaintiffs like him a second bite at the apple.", "start": 1616.62, "stop": 1625.133, "duration": 8.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let's look at the hypothetical.", "start": 1625.133, "stop": 1627.523, "duration": 2.39}, {"text": "Take it out of the facts of this case.", "start": 1627.523, "stop": 1629.976, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "There are two supervisors, each of them have anti-military animus, and they both report that this gentleman was late when he wasn't.", "start": 1629.976, "stop": 1644.092, "duration": 14.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1644.092, "stop": 1644.747, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Absolutely a falsehood.", "start": 1644.747, "stop": 1646.421, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "They go in, they report it to Miss Buck.", "start": 1646.421, "stop": 1650.215, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "Miss Buck does an investigation.", "start": 1650.215, "stop": 1653.873, "duration": 3.66}, {"text": "There are no witnesses.", "start": 1653.873, "stop": 1656.119, "duration": 2.25}, {"text": "There is no one else to prove that they came in late.", "start": 1656.119, "stop": 1661.836, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "She just takes the supervisors' word.", "start": 1661.836, "stop": 1667.256, "duration": 5.42}, {"text": "She looks at their report moments after the employee didn't show up, and she says: He's a late-goer.", "start": 1667.256, "stop": 1677.456, "duration": 10.2}, {"text": "I don't know anything about anti-animus; I simply fired him because two supervisors who are trustworthy, I've looked at their files, they've never lied about anything before, they are pretty honest people.", "start": 1677.456, "stop": 1692.513, "duration": 15.06}, {"text": "What happens in that situation?", "start": 1692.513, "stop": 1696.448, "duration": 3.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think in that situation, consistent with the \"cat's paw\" analysis, with the facts that you set up, the two supervisors so dominated her decision that there would be likely a finding that the case goes to the jury.", "start": 1696.448, "stop": 1708.661, "duration": 12.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "How?", "start": 1708.661, "stop": 1708.926, "duration": 0.26}, {"text": "She went and looked for witnesses, didn't find them.", "start": 1708.926, "stop": 1711.705, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "She looked at their records.", "start": 1711.705, "stop": 1715.582, "duration": 3.88}, {"text": "She did -- what happened here; other people have complained about these people, don't particularly like them.", "start": 1715.582, "stop": 1723.452, "duration": 7.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there being no other input whatsoever beyond that, there still is the domination issue.", "start": 1723.452, "stop": 1730.794, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "If I change your hypothetical just a little bit and say that all of what you said is true, but in addition to that the fellow who got fired has a 10-year history of being late and she looked at that history, I think that she's now made an independent decision, which is what happened in this case, and therefore under the Seventh Circuit's rule no liability attaches and that's the right result.", "start": 1730.794, "stop": 1755.112, "duration": 24.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's the question.", "start": 1755.112, "stop": 1756.032, "duration": 0.92}, {"text": "You just added a very important fact, which is a 10-year history of being late.", "start": 1756.032, "stop": 1761.764, "duration": 5.73}, {"text": "But on this day he wasn't late.", "start": 1761.764, "stop": 1764.654, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "On this day the two supervisors made it up.", "start": 1764.654, "stop": 1769.041, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "Would she have fired him absent that report?", "start": 1769.041, "stop": 1775.663, "duration": 6.62}, {"text": "Isn't that what the jury has to decide?", "start": 1775.663, "stop": 1778.049, "duration": 2.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that is what the jury has to decide, but I'm not sure that case in the latter extended hypothetical gets that far.", "start": 1778.049, "stop": 1786.375, "duration": 8.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what this circuit's \"cat's paw\" theory does and what others do say, if she engaged in any investigation there's no liability.", "start": 1786.375, "stop": 1796.357, "duration": 9.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I disagree with that a little bit.", "start": 1796.357, "stop": 1799.356, "duration": 3}, {"text": "I don't think if she engaged in any investigation that absolves of liability.", "start": 1799.356, "stop": 1803.478, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "I think if she engages in a good faith investigation it absolves of liability.", "start": 1803.478, "stop": 1807.756, "duration": 4.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was it -- what was it here?", "start": 1807.756, "stop": 1809.429, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "Because when -- what was his name -- Korenchuk?", "start": 1809.429, "stop": 1815.224, "duration": 5.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1815.224, "stop": 1816.363, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--takes him into Buck's office and Buck hands him the pink slip and says, \"You're fired\", that the jury could have credited that evidence.", "start": 1816.363, "stop": 1832.106, "duration": 15.74}, {"text": "He was given no opportunity to explain the situation.", "start": 1832.106, "stop": 1840.021, "duration": 7.91}, {"text": "What kind of investigation?", "start": 1840.021, "stop": 1843.305, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "What -- she looked at his personnel file.", "start": 1843.305, "stop": 1847.364, "duration": 4.06}, {"text": "What else was the investigation?", "start": 1847.364, "stop": 1851.08, "duration": 3.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I will answer that.", "start": 1851.08, "stop": 1854.044, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "Before I get to that, I disagree with the point about he wasn't given an opportunity to explain.", "start": 1854.044, "stop": 1858.529, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "I think the record is clear he was given an opportunity to explain.", "start": 1858.529, "stop": 1862.541, "duration": 4.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "When?", "start": 1862.541, "stop": 1863.528, "duration": 0.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "At the -- two times.", "start": 1863.528, "stop": 1864.994, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "At the time he was discharged, on the day that Korenchuk brings him in, Korenchuk says:", "start": 1864.994, "stop": 1869.509, "duration": 4.52}, {"text": "\"I was looking for you and couldn't find you. \"", "start": 1869.509, "stop": 1872.602, "duration": 3.09}, {"text": "And in the record, in fact, Staub gave an explanation of his whereabouts.", "start": 1872.602, "stop": 1876.709, "duration": 4.11}, {"text": "Buck was there.", "start": 1876.709, "stop": 1877.773, "duration": 1.06}, {"text": "She heard it.", "start": 1877.773, "stop": 1878.366, "duration": 0.59}, {"text": "The second time is, approximately 5 days later, he files a five-page long grievance stating all--", "start": 1878.366, "stop": 1886.125, "duration": 7.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is after he got his pink slip.", "start": 1886.125, "stop": 1887.798, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "What -- what point -- when Korenchuk takes him into -- takes Staub into Buck's office, according to his testimony, which the jury could credit, he wasn't asked a thing.", "start": 1887.798, "stop": 1906.867, "duration": 19.07}, {"text": "She just said: Here's your pink slip; you're fired.", "start": 1906.867, "stop": 1909.975, "duration": 3.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think the record shows he did give an explanation of his whereabouts.", "start": 1909.975, "stop": 1916.179, "duration": 6.2}, {"text": "The record also shows that he filed a five-page grievance contesting that action.", "start": 1916.179, "stop": 1921.844, "duration": 5.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "After he was fired.", "start": 1921.844, "stop": 1923.388, "duration": 1.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "After he was fired.", "start": 1923.388, "stop": 1924.387, "duration": 1}, {"text": "And that Buck carefully investigated that and 5 days after it was filed gave him a letter saying: I have looked into it, I have considered all your arguments, including your argument that you were discharged on account of your military service, but I don't credit it.", "start": 1924.387, "stop": 1939.852, "duration": 15.47}, {"text": "And therefore, I'm sustaining the discharge.", "start": 1939.852, "stop": 1943.037, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "And that is absolutely -- Mr. Staub knew that that works for him, because in 1998 he invoked the same procedure when he was discharged the first time for similar reasons and he was conditionally reinstated to employment at Proctor Hospital.", "start": 1943.037, "stop": 1960.718, "duration": 17.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did I understand you to say that you do agree with the Seventh Circuit's \"cat's paw\" approach to this?", "start": 1960.718, "stop": 1972.526, "duration": 11.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I do agree with it.", "start": 1972.526, "stop": 1973.93, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "The Mr. Staub and others like him a second bite at the apple.", "start": 1973.93, "stop": 1982.334, "duration": 8.4}, {"text": "But he has to demonstrate that the person who possessed animus exercised so much control over the decisionmaker that that person became the true decisionmaker.", "start": 1982.334, "stop": 1992.843, "duration": 10.51}, {"text": "And that simply doesn't work in this case for a number of reasons.", "start": 1992.843, "stop": 1996.438, "duration": 3.6}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Before you -- how is that consistent with the statutory language that requires that this discrimination simply be a motivating factor?", "start": 1996.438, "stop": 2003.434, "duration": 7}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "The answer to that is, the statute sets forth five factors, four or five factors, and says that one of the four or five employment actions has to be a motivating factor in arriving at the decision.", "start": 2003.434, "stop": 2022.74, "duration": 19.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can we -- let's look at the statutory factors.", "start": 2022.74, "stop": 2027.704, "duration": 4.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 2027.704, "stop": 2028.316, "duration": 0.61}, {"text": "It's 4311(a).", "start": 2028.316, "stop": 2032.453, "duration": 4.14}, {"text": "And it says--", "start": 2032.453, "stop": 2036.138, "duration": 3.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "And where are you reading it from?", "start": 2036.138, "stop": 2038.825, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--From the third line -- well, I'm sorry, I can't tell you what line it is.", "start": 2038.825, "stop": 2042.183, "duration": 3.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Page 3 of the blue brief.", "start": 2042.183, "stop": 2044.028, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "It says that there are five actions that are prohibited: Denial of initial employment, reemployment, retention in employment, promotion, or any benefit of employment.", "start": 2044.028, "stop": 2055.648, "duration": 11.62}, {"text": "And it says that an employer cannot take action, one of those actions, on the basis of four factors: Membership, application for membership, performance, service -- or service of obligation in the uniformed services.", "start": 2055.648, "stop": 2073.655, "duration": 18.01}, {"text": "So there has to be something to connect one of those factors to one of those five actions.", "start": 2073.655, "stop": 2081.245, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "And that's the literal meaning of the statute.", "start": 2081.245, "stop": 2086.009, "duration": 4.76}, {"text": "And I think the Seventh Circuit's view is absolutely consistent with that.", "start": 2086.009, "stop": 2090.791, "duration": 4.78}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm sorry.", "start": 2090.791, "stop": 2091.758, "duration": 0.97}, {"text": "The statute says is a motivating -- one of those four things, membership, application, et cetera, is a motivating factor in the action.", "start": 2091.758, "stop": 2099.787, "duration": 8.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Correct.", "start": 2099.787, "stop": 2100.707, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And I understood your position to be that the supervisor has to have such dominant control that it's the \"Cat's Paw\".", "start": 2100.707, "stop": 2107.924, "duration": 7.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "That the subordinate's motivation is imputed actually to the decisionmaker, and ultimately to the employer.", "start": 2107.924, "stop": 2116.718, "duration": 8.79}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I guess where I'm having trouble following you is the total domination-motivating factor.", "start": 2116.718, "stop": 2123.901, "duration": 7.18}, {"text": "It seems like a much more stringent test that the Seventh Circuit has adopted.", "start": 2123.901, "stop": 2128.557, "duration": 4.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think in the context of this case, Your Honor, it is not, because the definition of \"employer\" here not only includes Proctor Hospital, what you might call the ultimate employer, but it also includes the person who made the adverse employment decision.", "start": 2128.557, "stop": 2145.205, "duration": 16.65}, {"text": "And in this case, it's Linda Buck.", "start": 2145.205, "stop": 2147.002, "duration": 1.8}, {"text": "And this statute creates personal liability for Ms. Buck or anybody else who makes a decision if it's based on one of these factors contained in the statute.", "start": 2147.002, "stop": 2157.542, "duration": 10.54}, {"text": "I don't think there is any way a jury would be allowed to consider whether or not Ms. Buck is in violation of the statute because there is an absolute dearth of evidence that any of these factors motivated the decision she made.", "start": 2157.542, "stop": 2169.896, "duration": 12.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that assumes that the employment decision is solely hers.", "start": 2169.896, "stop": 2175.129, "duration": 5.23}, {"text": "It's hers, not based on her peccadilloes; it's hers based on the information that she has gathered.", "start": 2175.129, "stop": 2182.098, "duration": 6.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I agree.", "start": 2182.098, "stop": 2182.582, "duration": 0.48}, {"text": "It is hers to the extent that she makes a good faith investigation into the background facts.", "start": 2182.582, "stop": 2189.514, "duration": 6.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "But -- but she's not acting in a vacuum.", "start": 2189.514, "stop": 2191.655, "duration": 2.14}, {"text": "She's acting on information that has been supplied to her by people who are authorized to supply that to her in the employment context.", "start": 2191.655, "stop": 2200.292, "duration": 8.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "And in this case, she is acting on an awful lot of information.", "start": 2200.292, "stop": 2203.774, "duration": 3.48}, {"text": "They pick out--", "start": 2203.774, "stop": 2204.414, "duration": 0.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "We are now talking past the individual case.", "start": 2204.414, "stop": 2207.319, "duration": 2.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Okay.", "start": 2207.319, "stop": 2207.694, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am talking about just the legal analysis, which is: She is a decisionmaker, but there are multiple actors on behalf of the employer.", "start": 2207.694, "stop": 2218.675, "duration": 10.98}, {"text": "That's your adversary's position -- or participating in the process.", "start": 2218.675, "stop": 2222.781, "duration": 4.11}, {"text": "And they are saying if any of those actors in the process has been delegated employment duties that permit them to participate in this way, then if what motivates them is bias of this kind, then the employer is responsible, not just for Ms. Buck's activities, but for the two supervisors' discriminatory activities.", "start": 2222.781, "stop": 2249.021, "duration": 26.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "That would lead to a never-ending chain of looking backwards all the time over the course of perhaps a very long employment history to scour the record to determine, is there one single or two single actions out there that may somehow have come forward and caused this termination?", "start": 2249.021, "stop": 2266.921, "duration": 17.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in most situations an employer comes in and says: I fired X for X, Y, and Z reasons.", "start": 2266.921, "stop": 2275.475, "duration": 8.55}, {"text": "And if they don't mention one of those inconsequential or immaterial reports, why would a court rely on it at all?", "start": 2275.475, "stop": 2287.396, "duration": 11.92}, {"text": "It's not a motivating factor.", "start": 2287.396, "stop": 2288.737, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not sure I thoroughly understand the hypothetical, but if the true decisionmaker there comes forward and says, I didn't know about this, I didn't rely upon it, I don't think that the animus can be imputed to the decisionmaker.", "start": 2288.737, "stop": 2305.198, "duration": 16.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why is this so complicated?", "start": 2305.198, "stop": 2306.247, "duration": 1.05}, {"text": "I'm probably missing something.", "start": 2306.247, "stop": 2307.682, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think--", "start": 2307.682, "stop": 2308.434, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the thing -- but it doesn't help you, I don't think, if it isn't complicated.", "start": 2308.434, "stop": 2312.056, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "That is, because of Burlington we are only talking about a certain number of employees who could make an employer responsible.", "start": 2312.056, "stop": 2322.534, "duration": 10.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Right.", "start": 2322.534, "stop": 2322.862, "duration": 0.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 2322.862, "stop": 2323.427, "duration": 0.57}, {"text": "So those are supervisory people, we'll call them.", "start": 2323.427, "stop": 2325.174, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Correct.", "start": 2325.174, "stop": 2325.548, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, why don't we just stop there and just say, we have a statute, the statute says that if -- if a bad motive was a motivating -- had to be a motivating factor, discriminatory -- discriminatory motivating factor in the dismissal, then, unless you can prove an affirmative defense, you lose.", "start": 2325.548, "stop": 2350.022, "duration": 24.47}, {"text": "Why do we have to have something special if one of these small group of employees happens to be the person who said the last words or happens to be somebody who told somebody who said the last words or happens to be somebody who told the somebody the something-or-other?", "start": 2350.022, "stop": 2364.777, "duration": 14.76}, {"text": "You are just looking for one thing.", "start": 2364.777, "stop": 2366.279, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "And there could be five zillion fact situations.", "start": 2366.279, "stop": 2369.714, "duration": 3.43}, {"text": "So why something special?", "start": 2369.714, "stop": 2371.808, "duration": 2.09}, {"text": "Why did the Seventh Circuit say where it's not the guy who said the last words you have to show, quote, \"singular influence\"?", "start": 2371.808, "stop": 2378.898, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "Why singular influence?", "start": 2378.898, "stop": 2381.211, "duration": 2.31}, {"text": "Why not just what the statute says, that it was -- that it led to the -- what she said led to the discriminatory motive being a motivating factor, period, end of the matter.", "start": 2381.211, "stop": 2395.626, "duration": 14.42}, {"text": "No special \"cat's paw\" rule, no special anything rule.", "start": 2395.626, "stop": 2398.406, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "No consideration of proximate cause, either.", "start": 2398.406, "stop": 2400.204, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, no.", "start": 2400.204, "stop": 2400.813, "duration": 0.61}, {"text": "Of course you have to show proximate cause.", "start": 2400.813, "stop": 2403.796, "duration": 2.98}, {"text": "You have to show cause.", "start": 2403.796, "stop": 2404.903, "duration": 1.11}, {"text": "You always do.", "start": 2404.903, "stop": 2406.388, "duration": 1.49}, {"text": "I'm just saying, why have a special rule?", "start": 2406.388, "stop": 2409.216, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "Why not have a special rule if somebody was on the second floor?", "start": 2409.216, "stop": 2411.93, "duration": 2.71}, {"text": "You wouldn't think of that.", "start": 2411.93, "stop": 2413.26, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "So if you were not going to do it because the person's on the second floor, why do it because they happen to be somebody who told somebody rather than somebody who was the person who was told?", "start": 2413.26, "stop": 2422.615, "duration": 9.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because to motivate -- to be motivated by one of these factors, there has to be some element of proximate causation.", "start": 2422.615, "stop": 2430.348, "duration": 7.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Fine.", "start": 2430.348, "stop": 2430.582, "duration": 0.23}, {"text": "You are perfectly entitled to say that.", "start": 2430.582, "stop": 2432.158, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "But what I don't see that you are entitled to say are the words that the Seventh Circuit used, which is: You have to show jury that there was sufficient evidence to support a finding of singular influence.", "start": 2432.158, "stop": 2444.34, "duration": 12.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that--", "start": 2444.34, "stop": 2445.214, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "That doesn't just sound like it was a motivating cause.", "start": 2445.214, "stop": 2448.466, "duration": 3.25}, {"text": "That sounds like something really special.", "start": 2448.466, "stop": 2450.307, "duration": 1.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think that that is the Seventh Circuit's way of saying proximate cause.", "start": 2450.307, "stop": 2455.663, "duration": 5.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Ah, okay.", "start": 2455.663, "stop": 2456.74, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "So why don't we say: Seventh Circuit, if that's your way of saying it is just a normal thing like cause, we accept that, but please don't use those words.", "start": 2456.74, "stop": 2466.348, "duration": 9.61}, {"text": "And because you might have used -- you might have used them meaning something else, we will send this back so we are certain that what you are doing is applying the same test to everything.", "start": 2466.348, "stop": 2476.015, "duration": 9.67}, {"text": "In other words, was it a motivating factor?", "start": 2476.015, "stop": 2477.859, "duration": 1.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think you could say that.", "start": 2477.859, "stop": 2480.781, "duration": 2.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2480.781, "stop": 2481.421, "duration": 0.64}, {"text": "That seems like a good resolution of this case to me.", "start": 2481.421, "stop": 2484.669, "duration": 3.25}, {"text": "I don't know if it does to them.", "start": 2484.669, "stop": 2485.807, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that you've misread -- I think that you've misread the \"cat's paw\" principle of the court of appeals.", "start": 2485.807, "stop": 2495.068, "duration": 9.26}, {"text": "I don't think that it is, to them, a determination of proximate cause at all.", "start": 2495.068, "stop": 2502.676, "duration": 7.61}, {"text": "As I understand their opinion, they say that the statute requires that the -- let me get the right language here -- that the discriminatory, prohibited discriminatory factor, must have been a motivating factor in the employer's action.", "start": 2502.676, "stop": 2526.885, "duration": 24.21}, {"text": "And they say that means it must have motivated the person who took the employer's action.", "start": 2526.885, "stop": 2535.24, "duration": 8.35}, {"text": "It's not a motivating factor in the employer's action unless the person who took the action on behalf of the employer had that as its motive.", "start": 2535.24, "stop": 2544.752, "duration": 9.51}, {"text": "Then the court of appeals makes an exception: However, if the person who appears to be taking the action on behalf of the employer is really not the person who took the action, but was totally under the control of a subordinate who -- and the person just swallowed that subordinate's determination, then we will hold, even though the ultimate firing -- the person who signed the pink slip, even though that person didn't have the motive -- if in fact the decision was effectively the decision of a lower subordinate, we will hold the employer.", "start": 2544.752, "stop": 2581.002, "duration": 36.25}, {"text": "It has nothing to do with proximate cause.", "start": 2581.002, "stop": 2583.439, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "It has to do with the text that it has to be a motivating factor in the employer's action; not a motivating factor somewhere down the line, but in the employer's action.", "start": 2583.439, "stop": 2595.637, "duration": 12.2}, {"text": "That's how I read the court of appeals opinion.", "start": 2595.637, "stop": 2598.07, "duration": 2.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "And I agree with that, and we get back to the notion that in this case, it was Ms. Buck who made the decision.", "start": 2598.07, "stop": 2605.725, "duration": 7.65}, {"text": "She made the--", "start": 2605.725, "stop": 2606.411, "duration": 0.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the--", "start": 2606.411, "stop": 2606.567, "duration": 0.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I'm sorry.", "start": 2606.567, "stop": 2607.441, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But Ms. Buck never would have made this decision if Korenchuk hadn't come in and said: Here's Staub, he's goofing off; he was told to tell me when he was going to be absent, and he didn't.", "start": 2607.441, "stop": 2626.435, "duration": 18.99}, {"text": "Korenchuk, who has the absent -- is a motivating factor certainly in what happened to Mr. Staub, because if you didn't have Mr. Korenchuk marching Staub into Buck's office he would have retained his job.", "start": 2626.435, "stop": 2646.721, "duration": 20.29}, {"text": "Wasn't his last -- his most recent performance rating very good?", "start": 2646.721, "stop": 2653.626, "duration": 6.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Only on one respect.", "start": 2653.626, "stop": 2654.874, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "He received a technical \"very good\", but with respect to the narrative portion of that evaluation it says:", "start": 2654.874, "stop": 2661.402, "duration": 6.53}, {"text": "\"I want you to stay in the department when you are being paid to work and not to be out wandering around. \"", "start": 2661.402, "stop": 2665.446, "duration": 4.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "In any case, there was no indication, apart from Korenchuk's coming in, that Buck would have taken any adverse action against Staub.", "start": 2665.446, "stop": 2680.271, "duration": 14.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think we know the answer to that.", "start": 2680.271, "stop": 2682.533, "duration": 2.26}, {"text": "It was--", "start": 2682.533, "stop": 2683.254, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's not the point.", "start": 2683.254, "stop": 2684.518, "duration": 1.26}, {"text": "It seems to me you have to establish -- we are not going to second-guess the jury determination here.", "start": 2684.518, "stop": 2690.391, "duration": 5.87}, {"text": "I understood your point to be that there's a difference between a motivating factor in the decision, which means the person who made the decision on behalf of the employer must have had that motive, and on the other hand, a factor which was relevant to the decision, or a factor which influenced the decision.", "start": 2690.391, "stop": 2710.009, "duration": 19.62}, {"text": "That's quite different from a motivating factor in the decision.", "start": 2710.009, "stop": 2714.366, "duration": 4.36}, {"text": "You have to get us to believe -- and I'm not sure we will -- that motivating factor in the decision refers to motive on the part of the person who made the decision.", "start": 2714.366, "stop": 2725.907, "duration": 11.54}, {"text": "That's essentially your point, isn't it?", "start": 2725.907, "stop": 2727.938, "duration": 2.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 2727.938, "stop": 2728.375, "duration": 0.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then you can't agree with me, because my question was why would that be?", "start": 2728.375, "stop": 2733.5, "duration": 5.13}, {"text": "You have two people, A and B, they are both supervisors; in the one case B fires the employee because he is in the Army, and he says it: Ha, ha, that's why I'm doing it.", "start": 2733.5, "stop": 2747.008, "duration": 13.51}, {"text": "In the second case he fires the employee because he thought the employee was, in one of Justice Sotomayor's hypotheticals or anyone else, he fires him for a perfectly good reason, but A has lied about it.", "start": 2747.008, "stop": 2761.639, "duration": 14.63}, {"text": "And the reason A lied about it was because she wanted to tell him a lie so B would fire the employee, and her reason is because he's in the Army.", "start": 2761.639, "stop": 2771.31, "duration": 9.67}, {"text": "Those two situations, the second seems to me one of 80 -- 80 million situations, fact-related, that could arise, and I don't know why we want a special standard for such a situation.", "start": 2771.31, "stop": 2784.599, "duration": 13.29}, {"text": "Why not just ask the overall question, was this action an action that was -- in which the bad motive was a motivating factor.", "start": 2784.599, "stop": 2799, "duration": 14.4}, {"text": "Forget psychoanalysis of A.", "start": 2799, "stop": 2801.608, "duration": 2.61}, {"text": "B is good enough -- or vice versa.", "start": 2801.608, "stop": 2805.59, "duration": 3.98}, {"text": "That was my question.", "start": 2805.59, "stop": 2807.107, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "And in B, the employer could not be liable.", "start": 2807.107, "stop": 2812.418, "duration": 5.31}, {"text": "In B the person who made the decision, the employer, was not motivated by one of the factors in the statute; that person couldn't be liable.", "start": 2812.418, "stop": 2824.662, "duration": 12.24}, {"text": "If that person can't be liable, how can that employer of that person be vicariously liable?", "start": 2824.662, "stop": 2829.72, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "I don't think they can.", "start": 2829.72, "stop": 2830.582, "duration": 0.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because together they dismissed the employee.", "start": 2830.582, "stop": 2834.003, "duration": 3.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, no.", "start": 2834.003, "stop": 2834.518, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "One by supplying the false statement, the other by acting on it.", "start": 2834.518, "stop": 2839.5, "duration": 4.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I disagree on that.", "start": 2839.5, "stop": 2840.841, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "A corporation can only act through its agents.", "start": 2840.841, "stop": 2843.201, "duration": 2.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "They are both agents.", "start": 2843.201, "stop": 2844.718, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "That's why I made them both Burlington people.", "start": 2844.718, "stop": 2847.669, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "I wanted to get them in the group.", "start": 2847.669, "stop": 2850.056, "duration": 2.39}, {"text": "They both have the same Burlington status, so we get that issue out of it.", "start": 2850.056, "stop": 2855.367, "duration": 5.31}, {"text": "And together they fire this individual.", "start": 2855.367, "stop": 2858.834, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "In the absence of either the one or the other, he wouldn't have been fired.", "start": 2858.834, "stop": 2863.662, "duration": 4.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have listened to the hypothetical long enough that I have lost track of who made the decision to fire him.", "start": 2863.662, "stop": 2872.673, "duration": 9.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I feel I'm going to get nowhere pursuing this hypothetical further.", "start": 2872.673, "stop": 2876.967, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "So I will drop it and say--", "start": 2876.967, "stop": 2878.577, "duration": 1.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 2878.577, "stop": 2879.481, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Answer it as you wish or as you understand it.", "start": 2879.481, "stop": 2881.592, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "As I understand it, the second person in the hypothetical had no motivation whatsoever under the statute to cause the discharge and therefore the employer wouldn't be liable for that decision.", "start": 2881.592, "stop": 2893.197, "duration": 11.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, your position is -- it coincides with the Seventh Circuit, but it is in opposition to the Secretary of Labor's commentary on how this works.", "start": 2893.197, "stop": 2908.284, "duration": 15.09}, {"text": "The Secretary of Labor's commentary is it's a motivating factor, and if Korenchuk precipitates this whole thing, that's a motivating factor.", "start": 2908.284, "stop": 2919.359, "duration": 11.07}, {"text": "Do we -- I mean, this is the Secretary of Labor administers the statute.", "start": 2919.359, "stop": 2925.901, "duration": 6.54}, {"text": "Do we give any weight to the government's official position on what a motivating factor means?", "start": 2925.901, "stop": 2935.99, "duration": 10.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Normally you would give weight to the government's position, but I think the government's position has to be consistent with the precise language of the statute.", "start": 2935.99, "stop": 2943.722, "duration": 7.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "How does the Secretary of Labor administer this statute?", "start": 2943.722, "stop": 2948.425, "duration": 4.7}, {"text": "What are -- what are his or her responsibilities under the statute?", "start": 2948.425, "stop": 2952.189, "duration": 3.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "There can be a charge filed with the Secretary of Labor, which the Secretary of Labor would then investigate.", "start": 2952.189, "stop": 2956.954, "duration": 4.77}, {"text": "The Secretary of Labor has the option to bring an action should the Secretary choose to do so.", "start": 2956.954, "stop": 2962.604, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "But coterminously, the individual service person can bring an independent cause of action, and that's what happened in this case.", "start": 2962.604, "stop": 2969.479, "duration": 6.88}, {"text": "In this case there was no Secretary of Labor involvement.", "start": 2969.479, "stop": 2972.181, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, why isn't this just governed by the standard principles of tort for concurrent actors?", "start": 2972.181, "stop": 2978.506, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "Actor A was not negligent; actor B was; they both contributed to the accident.", "start": 2978.506, "stop": 2985.58, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "And we look to the Restatement of Torts, which is whether or not the wrongful actor made a significant contribution.", "start": 2985.58, "stop": 2993.235, "duration": 7.66}, {"text": "That's -- that's the end of it.", "start": 2993.235, "stop": 2994.109, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that the problem with this situation is, is that one of the actors here, the decision that she made, being Mulally, and that's with respect to whom the most evidence of animus was adduced, didn't commit an action that would be actionable under USERRA.", "start": 2994.109, "stop": 3012.6, "duration": 18.49}, {"text": "There -- there is no way that issuing the constructive advice record on January 27 violated the statute, even if it was motivated by animus.", "start": 3012.6, "stop": 3021.631, "duration": 9.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "But we are -- but we are talking about the test.", "start": 3021.631, "stop": 3025.596, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "The test I gave you is quite different from the \"cat's paw\" test.", "start": 3025.596, "stop": 3029.937, "duration": 4.34}, {"text": "And if you use the test something along the lines that I formulated, I don't know if that's precisely what the Restatement says--", "start": 3029.937, "stop": 3038.684, "duration": 8.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sure.", "start": 3038.684, "stop": 3038.949, "duration": 0.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--but to that general effect, the instruction given to the jury was really overprotective of your client, under the standard concurrent -- concurrent causation analysis.", "start": 3038.949, "stop": 3052.741, "duration": 13.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "The instruction may have been somewhat protective, but the problem is, prior to issuing that instruction the district court did no analysis whatsoever to determine if the instruction was warranted in the first place, and that was simply our point to the Seventh Circuit.", "start": 3052.741, "stop": 3070.78, "duration": 18.04}, {"text": "Before you allow this to fall into the lap of a jury and try and explain to a jury, as opposed to the Supreme Court, what it means to be a \"cat's paw\" in the agency theory, the district court should at least make an initial determination that that's what we have here.", "start": 3070.78, "stop": 3084.214, "duration": 13.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can I turn to the Secretary of Labor's regulations?", "start": 3084.214, "stop": 3088.398, "duration": 4.18}, {"text": "Are what we talking about anything more than the following statement in his commentary accompanying the final regs, namely that an employee, quote,", "start": 3088.398, "stop": 3100.846, "duration": 12.45}, {"text": "\"need not show that his or her protected activities or status was the sole cause of the employment action. \"", "start": 3100.846, "stop": 3107.159, "duration": 6.31}, {"text": "\"The person's activities or status need be only one of the factors that a truthful employer would list if asked for the reasons for its decision. \"", "start": 3107.159, "stop": 3117.513, "duration": 10.35}, {"text": "Is that -- is that the only--", "start": 3117.513, "stop": 3120.075, "duration": 2.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe that is the only thing with -- there may be a section later on, Your Honor, in the regs that deals with--", "start": 3120.075, "stop": 3125.993, "duration": 5.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--This is the one that the government refers to.", "start": 3125.993, "stop": 3127.959, "duration": 1.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That is certainly the commentary that goes with it.", "start": 3127.959, "stop": 3129.382, "duration": 1.42}, {"text": "I agree with that.", "start": 3129.382, "stop": 3129.491, "duration": 0.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "That doesn't seem to me to be so damning of your case.", "start": 3129.491, "stop": 3132.615, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "I think if this employer had been asked the reasons for its decision it would have given Ms. Buck's reasons.", "start": 3132.615, "stop": 3138.94, "duration": 6.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Ms. Buck would have said: I let him go because he has this veritable tsunami of bad behaviors, what he is accused of is absolutely consistent with it, and I made the decision.", "start": 3138.94, "stop": 3149.605, "duration": 10.66}, {"text": "Is it a truthful statement by her?", "start": 3149.605, "stop": 3151.215, "duration": 1.61}, {"text": "It is absolutely a truthful statement by her, and that was the reason for her actions.", "start": 3151.215, "stop": 3157.338, "duration": 6.12}, {"text": "I think Ms. Buck's consideration of the discharge decision wasn't limited to one source.", "start": 3157.338, "stop": 3169.286, "duration": 11.95}, {"text": "It clearly was not.", "start": 3169.286, "stop": 3170.363, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "No one shaped or directed the scope of her determination.", "start": 3170.363, "stop": 3173.081, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "Even more important, she gave Mr. Staub the opportunity to tell his side of the story.", "start": 3173.081, "stop": 3178.127, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "And after considering all that, she decided that his discharge was warranted.", "start": 3178.127, "stop": 3183.279, "duration": 5.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could a jury find from the testimony before -- before it, that at the time he received his pink slip -- let's not talk about the grievance after--", "start": 3183.279, "stop": 3196.134, "duration": 12.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 3196.134, "stop": 3196.446, "duration": 0.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--at the time he got the grievance slip, he was not given any opportunity to explain that this charge was not warranted, that he had tried to reach Korenchuk on the phone to tell him, we are going to lunch, and was unable to.", "start": 3196.446, "stop": 3219.606, "duration": 23.16}, {"text": "He did not have an opportunity to say that to Ms. Buck.", "start": 3219.606, "stop": 3222.858, "duration": 3.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Roy G. Davis", "textObjs": [{"text": "Again, Your Honor, I believe the record says -- and I apologize, I can't quote it from the page -- that in fact Mr. Staub protested that what he was accused of, i.e., not being where he was supposed to be, was wrong.", "start": 3222.858, "stop": 3236.584, "duration": 13.73}, {"text": "And he stated his version of it.", "start": 3236.584, "stop": 3239.365, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "If there are no other questions, Your Honor, I would respectfully request that the decision of the Seventh Circuit be affirmed.", "start": 3239.365, "stop": 3252.268, "duration": 12.9}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3252.268, "stop": 3252.689, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Davis.", "start": 3252.689, "stop": 3253.781, "duration": 1.09}, {"text": "Mr. Schnapper, you have 4 minutes remaining.", "start": 3253.781, "stop": 3256.562, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Schnapper, is that your recollection of this record, too, that he did state his version before he got the pink slip?", "start": 3256.562, "stop": 3270.042, "duration": 13.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it's somewhat unclear what happened.", "start": 3270.042, "stop": 3272.991, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "It's complicated by the fact that the defendant's account of why he was fired has changed.", "start": 3272.991, "stop": 3278.988, "duration": 6}, {"text": "One, the written explanation was that he never obeyed the rule for the 3 months it was in effect.", "start": 3278.988, "stop": 3285.844, "duration": 6.86}, {"text": "The explanation given by Buck was that she had been told that he wasn't -- couldn't have been found on the 19th.", "start": 3285.844, "stop": 3294.98, "duration": 9.14}, {"text": "The story that was given to Staub at the time was that Korenchuk couldn't find him on the 20th, so if he was responding to that he was responding to the wrong question.", "start": 3294.98, "stop": 3304.195, "duration": 9.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I don't think anybody thought that Buck would have fired him just for that one absence.", "start": 3304.195, "stop": 3307.584, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "That was the trigger.", "start": 3307.584, "stop": 3309.6, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "But it was the trigger that followed a long series of prior absences for which he had been disciplined before.", "start": 3309.6, "stop": 3317.111, "duration": 7.51}, {"text": "I don't see any inconsistency between those two versions.", "start": 3317.111, "stop": 3320.874, "duration": 3.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "But those aren't the versions in the written record at the time.", "start": 3320.874, "stop": 3326.997, "duration": 6.12}, {"text": "The written record at the time says he is fired because he has been breaking this rule ever since January.", "start": 3326.997, "stop": 3331.821, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "Nobody claims that's true.", "start": 3331.821, "stop": 3333.322, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "If I -- we -- a number of questions, I think particularly Justice Alito asked whether Congress would have intended the result in this case.", "start": 3333.322, "stop": 3343.363, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "We don't think it's as harsh as you do, but we think that the intent is particularly clear here.", "start": 3343.363, "stop": 3348.924, "duration": 5.56}, {"text": "Section 4301(1) says the purpose, the codified purpose, the purpose of the statute is to minimize the disadvantages to civilian careers that can result from service in the military.", "start": 3348.924, "stop": 3363.761, "duration": 14.84}, {"text": "And that it seems to me you have to read -- you have to read the rest of the statute.", "start": 3363.761, "stop": 3369.572, "duration": 5.81}, {"text": "Secondly, this USERRA is unique among employment statutes or close to it, because the employer has an economic incentive to break the law.", "start": 3369.572, "stop": 3379.379, "duration": 9.81}, {"text": "It's expensive to keep reservists on the books.", "start": 3379.379, "stop": 3382.33, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "And Mulally and Korenchuk objected to Staub working there precisely because it cost them more money when he went to drill, and it cost them more money when he was called up for operation Iraqi Freedom.", "start": 3382.33, "stop": 3394.95, "duration": 12.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, do you think that the standard for employer liability is different under this statute than under other federal antidiscrimination statutes?", "start": 3394.95, "stop": 3402.543, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "Is that what you were just suggesting?", "start": 3402.543, "stop": 3404.415, "duration": 1.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think there are particularly compelling textual reasons for the position we are urging here, other statutes have different language.", "start": 3404.415, "stop": 3414.912, "duration": 10.5}, {"text": "You might decide this case--", "start": 3414.912, "stop": 3418.253, "duration": 3.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if we were to hold here that the VII or under the ADEA or under the ADA?", "start": 3418.253, "stop": 3431.999, "duration": 13.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, we think that would be wrong for some of the reasons we set out in our brief, but you could write an opinion that only addressed it under USERRA and left those other questions open.", "start": 3431.999, "stop": 3439.931, "duration": 7.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why would Title VII be different?", "start": 3439.931, "stop": 3444.556, "duration": 4.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric Schnapper", "textObjs": [{"text": "Of the language in Title VII is similar to 4311(c)(1), but the language that I just read about the purpose isn't in Title VII.", "start": 3444.556, "stop": 3457.268, "duration": 12.71}, {"text": "So you could decide this case on somewhat narrower grounds and not reach every situation.", "start": 3457.268, "stop": 3464.954, "duration": 7.69}, {"text": "The -- the interpretation of USERRA adopted by the Seventh Circuit creates a serious loophole in the statute.", "start": 3464.954, "stop": 3474.979, "duration": 10.02}, {"text": "As a number of the amici have pointed out, the amici on the other side, employers typically make a disciplinary decision as a result of a bunch of different decisions.", "start": 3474.979, "stop": 3486.273, "duration": 11.29}, {"text": "The Seventh Circuit holds that so long as the employer divides up those responsibilities, USERRA will not apply to many of the decisions.", "start": 3486.273, "stop": 3496.61, "duration": 10.34}, {"text": "On their view, but USERRA applies only to what the last decisionmaker did.", "start": 3496.61, "stop": 3501.671, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "And the narrower her role, the narrower the protections of the statute.", "start": 3501.671, "stop": 3506.935, "duration": 5.26}, {"text": "This statute should not be read in that way.", "start": 3506.935, "stop": 3510.48, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "Not only because of the language that I have recounted, but because USERRA, it's reemployment rights and it's anti-discrimination rights play an essential role in the national defense.", "start": 3510.48, "stop": 3522.397, "duration": 11.92}, {"text": "They safeguard the livelihood of men and women who safeguard the nation.", "start": 3522.397, "stop": 3526.133, "duration": 3.74}, {"text": "And Congress wouldn't have wanted that statute read wrong.", "start": 3526.133, "stop": 3528.925, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 3528.925, "stop": 3531.457, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 3531.457, "stop": 3532.818, "duration": 1.36}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Roberts Court", "arguedOn": "Nov 2, 2010", "petitioner": "Vincent E. Staub", "respondent": "Proctor Hospital", "docket": "09-400", "citation": "562US411(2011)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/562/411", "lowerCourt": "United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit", "grantedOn": "Apr 19, 2010", "decidedOn": "Mar 1, 2011", "wikiData": {"title": "Staub v. Proctor Hospital", "Litigants": "Staub v. Proctor Hospital", "ArgueDate": "November 2", "ArgueYear": "2010", "DecideDate": "March 1", "DecideYear": "2011", "FullName": "Vincent E. Staub, Petitioner v. Proctor Hospital", "Docket": "09-400", "USVol": "562", "USPage": "411", "ParallelCitations": "131 S. Ct. 1186; 179 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 144; 79 U.S.L.W. 4126", "Prior": "", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "An employer may be held liable for employment discrimination based on the discriminatory animus of an employee who influenced, but did not make, the ultimate employment decision.", "SCOTUS": "20102016", "Majority": "Scalia", "JoinMajority": "Roberts, Kennedy, Ginsburg, Breyer, Alito, Sotomayor", "Concurrence": "Alito, Thomas (in judgment)", "Concurrence2": "", "Dissent": "", "JoinDissent": "", "NotParticipating": "Kagan", "LawsApplied": "[[Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act]]"}}